1
00:00:41,788 --> 00:00:42,748
Yes?

2
00:00:43,415 --> 00:00:46,584
Pierre, there's
an urgent call from France.

3
00:00:48,211 --> 00:00:50,129
After the concert.

4
00:00:53,883 --> 00:00:55,885
It's about your mother.

5
00:01:04,476 --> 00:01:05,477
Yes?

6
00:03:00,123 --> 00:03:02,459
Do you remember me?

7
00:03:03,627 --> 00:03:05,378
Fond de I'tang.

8
00:03:05,462 --> 00:03:07,839
"My father is coming for me
on Saturday."

9
00:03:09,507 --> 00:03:11,843
Ppinot.

10
00:03:11,884 --> 00:03:13,636
Of course.

11
00:03:15,012 --> 00:03:15,930
Ppinot.

12
00:03:16,972 --> 00:03:20,058
- How long has it been?
- About 50 years.

13
00:03:23,019 --> 00:03:24,437
Fond de I'tang.

14
00:03:27,607 --> 00:03:30,651
You're the little guy in the front row.

15
00:03:30,693 --> 00:03:32,778
And there you are.

16
00:03:32,862 --> 00:03:35,447
Do you remember the prefect's name?

17
00:03:35,531 --> 00:03:37,408
Clment Mathieu.

18
00:03:37,491 --> 00:03:38,951
Clment Mathieu.

19
00:03:40,869 --> 00:03:43,330
I wonder what happened to him.

20
00:03:45,373 --> 00:03:47,083
Open it.

21
00:03:51,671 --> 00:03:53,172
"Fond de I'tang.

22
00:03:53,255 --> 00:03:54,924
1949."

23
00:03:55,007 --> 00:03:58,719
Mathieu kept a journal
while he worked at Fond de I'tang.

24
00:03:58,761 --> 00:04:01,763
That's his story. Ours too.

25
00:04:03,014 --> 00:04:04,975
He wanted you to have it.

26
00:04:05,058 --> 00:04:09,020
I'd have preferred to deliver it
under different circumstances, but...

27
00:04:12,815 --> 00:04:15,067
"January 15, 1949.

28
00:04:16,151 --> 00:04:19,530
After failing for so long
in so many fields,

29
00:04:19,613 --> 00:04:22,699
I was sure the worst was still to come."

30
00:04:23,742 --> 00:04:28,037
It was a boarding school where
troubled children were rehabilitated.

31
00:04:28,788 --> 00:04:31,290
That's what the advertisement said.

32
00:04:31,332 --> 00:04:33,334
Fond de I'tang.

33
00:04:33,417 --> 00:04:36,545
Even the name seemed
to fit me like a glove.

34
00:04:37,838 --> 00:04:38,797
Hello.

35
00:04:40,257 --> 00:04:42,134
You're all alone?

36
00:04:42,717 --> 00:04:44,427
What are you doing there?

37
00:04:45,470 --> 00:04:47,639
Waiting for Saturday.

38
00:04:47,680 --> 00:04:49,015
Why?

39
00:04:50,349 --> 00:04:52,727
My father is coming for me.

40
00:04:52,810 --> 00:04:54,854
But it's not Saturday.

41
00:04:54,937 --> 00:04:55,855
Ppinot.

42
00:04:57,106 --> 00:04:58,232
Ppinot.

43
00:04:59,191 --> 00:05:02,652
Hello. I'm Clment Mathieu,
the new prefect.

44
00:05:04,613 --> 00:05:06,531
Have you done this type of work before?

45
00:05:06,614 --> 00:05:08,533
I taught some classes in private school.

46
00:05:08,616 --> 00:05:10,535
- What did you teach?
- Music.

47
00:05:10,618 --> 00:05:14,955
You'll like Rachin, our headmaster.
He used to play the trumpet.

48
00:05:15,039 --> 00:05:16,540
- Hello, Ppinot.
- Hello.

49
00:05:16,624 --> 00:05:19,001
His daughters. He lives right there.

50
00:05:21,378 --> 00:05:24,256
- You haven't met Mr. Rachin?
- Not yet, no.

51
00:05:24,339 --> 00:05:26,883
- Mrs. Boissemand recommended me.
- Really?

52
00:05:26,966 --> 00:05:29,010
That was old Maxence.

53
00:05:29,093 --> 00:05:32,305
He told me on the spot
that he was the school watchman,

54
00:05:32,346 --> 00:05:35,766
as well as its nurse,
storekeeper and glazier.

55
00:05:38,352 --> 00:05:41,647
- What is he doing?
- Serving detention for Mr. Rachin.

56
00:05:42,189 --> 00:05:45,275
Fifteen days of community work.
In other words, school drudge.

57
00:05:45,358 --> 00:05:47,861
What kind of children are they, exactly?

58
00:05:47,944 --> 00:05:50,071
- No one told you?
- No.

59
00:05:51,822 --> 00:05:54,450
My infirmary. I'll show you
my vegetable garden later.

60
00:05:54,492 --> 00:05:55,993
I'd like that.

61
00:05:58,704 --> 00:06:01,373
- Damn it! What have they done now?
- I'll help you.

62
00:06:01,456 --> 00:06:03,375
Are you Clment Mathieu?

63
00:06:03,416 --> 00:06:05,168
The headmaster...

64
00:06:05,251 --> 00:06:07,795
Rachin, the school's headmaster.

65
00:06:07,837 --> 00:06:09,964
Headmaster, I'm sorry...

66
00:06:10,006 --> 00:06:12,508
- Yes, you're late.
- I had the wrong bus schedule.

67
00:06:12,592 --> 00:06:14,427
Punctuality is essential here.

68
00:06:14,510 --> 00:06:16,178
Very well.

69
00:06:16,220 --> 00:06:17,179
Headmaster.

70
00:06:18,222 --> 00:06:19,640
Very well, Headmaster.

71
00:06:19,681 --> 00:06:21,350
Come with me.

72
00:06:22,017 --> 00:06:25,103
First you should study
the school regulations,

73
00:06:25,145 --> 00:06:28,147
then you can supervise
the 4:00 study period before you...

74
00:06:31,317 --> 00:06:33,736
What are you doing? Answer me.

75
00:06:33,778 --> 00:06:35,571
- Take this.
- It's my eye.

76
00:06:35,654 --> 00:06:38,699
Another trap. You can appreciate
our boarders' finer instincts.

77
00:06:38,741 --> 00:06:40,742
Get him over there.

78
00:06:40,784 --> 00:06:42,494
I'm blinded.

79
00:06:42,577 --> 00:06:45,372
Don't make a fuss. Show me.

80
00:06:45,455 --> 00:06:47,499
It's not pretty.

81
00:06:47,540 --> 00:06:49,667
Ring the bell. School assembly.

82
00:06:49,751 --> 00:06:52,503
- We should call a doctor.
- Do you know how much they charge?

83
00:06:52,587 --> 00:06:54,964
What did I say? Ring the assembly.

84
00:06:55,005 --> 00:06:56,340
The bell?

85
00:06:56,382 --> 00:06:58,759
Next to the door,
right in front of you.

86
00:06:58,801 --> 00:06:59,760
All right.

87
00:07:02,804 --> 00:07:04,264
Assembly.

88
00:07:05,682 --> 00:07:07,142
Assembly.

89
00:07:08,434 --> 00:07:11,270
- Are they always like that?
- Keep ringing the bell.

90
00:07:20,571 --> 00:07:22,322
Two abreast.

91
00:07:26,159 --> 00:07:28,661
Everybody in the schoolyard.
Assembly.

92
00:07:32,206 --> 00:07:33,624
Hurry up.

93
00:07:34,417 --> 00:07:36,502
Move faster. Be silent.

94
00:07:37,711 --> 00:07:39,421
- Chrome Dome.
- Be silent.

95
00:07:41,006 --> 00:07:42,924
- Chrome Dome.
- Be silent.

96
00:07:44,884 --> 00:07:45,969
Be silent.

97
00:07:46,052 --> 00:07:47,971
- I didn't say anything.
- Be silent.

98
00:07:54,685 --> 00:07:56,770
I called this assembly

99
00:07:56,812 --> 00:08:00,399
because of a despicable attempt
against old Maxence.

100
00:08:00,482 --> 00:08:04,486
Under our action-reaction rule,
the culprit will be severely punished.

101
00:08:06,029 --> 00:08:09,032
I want the culprit's name
within the next three seconds,

102
00:08:09,115 --> 00:08:12,201
or it's six hours of lock-up
for each one of you.

103
00:08:12,285 --> 00:08:16,747
Effective until he's betrayed
or gives himself up.

104
00:08:16,830 --> 00:08:18,248
Is that clear?

105
00:08:18,332 --> 00:08:19,958
One...

106
00:08:20,042 --> 00:08:21,460
Two...

107
00:08:21,543 --> 00:08:23,211
Three.

108
00:08:23,295 --> 00:08:24,713
No volunteers?

109
00:08:24,796 --> 00:08:27,132
Of course. Come closer.

110
00:08:28,967 --> 00:08:30,760
- Mathieu.
- Me?

111
00:08:30,802 --> 00:08:32,678
Come closer.

112
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:34,680
The school register, Mr. Chabert.

113
00:08:34,764 --> 00:08:36,181
Thank you.

114
00:08:36,265 --> 00:08:39,601
Mr. Mathieu, your new prefect,
has been spared your acquaintance.

115
00:08:39,685 --> 00:08:42,145
- Chrome Dome.
- Be silent.

116
00:08:42,187 --> 00:08:45,607
So he can choose
who goes first without bias.

117
00:08:49,569 --> 00:08:50,695
Be silent.

118
00:08:50,778 --> 00:08:52,780
Pick a name.

119
00:08:52,863 --> 00:08:54,532
At random?

120
00:08:56,617 --> 00:08:59,161
- A word of advice...
- Don't interfere. Go on.

121
00:09:02,622 --> 00:09:03,874
Boniface.

122
00:09:05,917 --> 00:09:07,961
Too bad. Chabert, get Boniface.

123
00:09:10,505 --> 00:09:12,923
- Sir, I didn't do anything.
- Shut up.

124
00:09:12,965 --> 00:09:15,718
- It's lousy, I didn't do anything.
- Watch your language.

125
00:09:15,801 --> 00:09:17,177
Move.

126
00:09:17,219 --> 00:09:19,429
- I won't go.
- I'll kick your backside for you.

127
00:09:19,513 --> 00:09:21,431
Be silent.

128
00:09:21,473 --> 00:09:23,892
Furthermore,
until I've found the culprit,

129
00:09:23,975 --> 00:09:26,978
there will be no recess
and no visitors.

130
00:09:27,061 --> 00:09:29,439
I advise you to give him up quickly.

131
00:09:29,522 --> 00:09:31,774
It's an encouragement to turn informer.

132
00:09:32,608 --> 00:09:35,444
You're full of noble illusions
like any new staff member.

133
00:09:35,486 --> 00:09:37,446
Come see me in eight days.

134
00:09:37,529 --> 00:09:40,699
You'll be replacing Mr. Rgent.
He'll explain your duties.

135
00:09:44,869 --> 00:09:46,746
Clean sheets.

136
00:09:46,830 --> 00:09:48,122
Thank you.

137
00:09:50,249 --> 00:09:52,168
Why are you leaving?

138
00:09:53,669 --> 00:09:55,880
Ten stitches.

139
00:09:55,963 --> 00:09:58,298
Cut with scissors.

140
00:09:58,340 --> 00:10:01,134
Just for confiscating
Mouton's cigarettes.

141
00:10:01,218 --> 00:10:03,887
- Mouton?
- The boy's name is Mouton.

142
00:10:05,889 --> 00:10:07,932
And Mouton's still here?

143
00:10:10,601 --> 00:10:13,521
By the way, Le Querrec
booby-trapped Maxence's door.

144
00:10:13,562 --> 00:10:16,440
I heard him talking about it
in the corridor.

145
00:10:16,523 --> 00:10:19,318
- And you didn't say anything?
- I didn't want to miss the bus.

146
00:10:20,277 --> 00:10:22,863
Old Maxence punished him
for breaking some glass panes.

147
00:10:22,946 --> 00:10:25,156
Simple revenge. That's just his style.

148
00:10:26,116 --> 00:10:27,408
Le Querrec.

149
00:10:28,826 --> 00:10:31,162
Don't forget that name: Le Querrec.

150
00:10:31,245 --> 00:10:32,663
- Morhange too.
- Yes.

151
00:10:32,747 --> 00:10:35,624
Morhange doesn't talk much,
but keep an eye on him.

152
00:10:35,708 --> 00:10:38,585
Looks like an angel,
acts like the devil.

153
00:10:38,669 --> 00:10:40,629
Action-reaction.

154
00:10:40,712 --> 00:10:42,631
That's all they understand.

155
00:10:46,009 --> 00:10:47,927
They're all yours.

156
00:10:49,595 --> 00:10:51,681
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

157
00:10:59,271 --> 00:11:00,939
Our benefactresses.

158
00:11:01,023 --> 00:11:02,899
The timetable's over there.

159
00:11:02,983 --> 00:11:05,360
Classes were shared
between the headmaster,

160
00:11:05,443 --> 00:11:07,362
who taught French and History,

161
00:11:07,445 --> 00:11:10,907
and Mr. Langlois,
who taught every other subject.

162
00:11:10,990 --> 00:11:13,159
Mr. Langlois, here's the new prefect.

163
00:11:13,242 --> 00:11:14,952
Clment Mathieu.

164
00:11:15,035 --> 00:11:18,580
- A prefect at your age?
- Yes, but I used to teach.

165
00:11:18,664 --> 00:11:20,916
Very well then.

166
00:11:24,794 --> 00:11:27,130
And he's the funny one.

167
00:11:27,172 --> 00:11:31,008
Take your study period. You're late.
No need to show you the way.

168
00:11:53,487 --> 00:11:55,322
Watch out. Chrome Dome's coming.

169
00:12:03,288 --> 00:12:05,123
Gentlemen.

170
00:12:10,002 --> 00:12:11,879
No smoking during class.

171
00:12:13,297 --> 00:12:15,883
The rules apply to everyone.
Even you, sir.

172
00:12:19,803 --> 00:12:22,305
Give it back.

173
00:12:22,389 --> 00:12:23,807
Be quiet.

174
00:12:23,890 --> 00:12:25,392
Give it back.

175
00:12:26,309 --> 00:12:28,394
Be silent.

176
00:12:28,436 --> 00:12:29,896
Give it back.

177
00:12:33,149 --> 00:12:36,110
An auspicious beginning.
Congratulations, Mathieu.

178
00:12:36,193 --> 00:12:37,736
Sit.

179
00:12:40,364 --> 00:12:41,615
Of course.

180
00:12:41,656 --> 00:12:44,367
You again.

181
00:12:44,451 --> 00:12:47,579
What did he do?

182
00:12:47,662 --> 00:12:49,080
Nothing, Headmaster.

183
00:12:50,123 --> 00:12:53,334
What do you mean, "nothing?"
You were about to punish him.

184
00:12:53,417 --> 00:12:55,794
I asked him to go to the blackboard

185
00:12:55,878 --> 00:12:58,130
and I was just telling them
to be silent.

186
00:12:58,213 --> 00:13:00,841
Not a minute too soon.

187
00:13:01,758 --> 00:13:03,677
Don't make me come back.

188
00:13:09,807 --> 00:13:12,226
Stand in the corner.

189
00:13:13,394 --> 00:13:15,271
Very well.

190
00:13:15,312 --> 00:13:20,150
Now that you've come to know me,
we need to set things straight.

191
00:13:20,234 --> 00:13:23,195
Right now,
one of your classmates is in lock-up.

192
00:13:23,278 --> 00:13:25,155
For no good reason.

193
00:13:25,238 --> 00:13:28,408
I may not look like much
but I'm no fool.

194
00:13:28,491 --> 00:13:30,368
I know who did it.

195
00:13:30,451 --> 00:13:33,412
He has 15 seconds to give himself up.

196
00:13:36,457 --> 00:13:38,250
I'm waiting.

197
00:13:39,918 --> 00:13:42,754
You'll regret it. Five seconds left.

198
00:13:44,673 --> 00:13:46,800
Too late.

199
00:13:47,634 --> 00:13:49,052
Le Querrec.

200
00:13:50,094 --> 00:13:51,554
Who is Le Querrec?

201
00:13:52,471 --> 00:13:54,557
I am, sir.

202
00:13:55,724 --> 00:13:57,434
What a surprise.

203
00:13:57,935 --> 00:14:01,188
- You hurt Mr. Maxence.
- No, sir. I didn't do it.

204
00:14:01,271 --> 00:14:03,899
- That wasn't a question.
- I didn't do anything.

205
00:14:03,940 --> 00:14:06,943
Between the two of us, I wonder
who the headmaster will believe.

206
00:14:07,026 --> 00:14:12,198
I need someone dependable
to keep an eye on things while I'm gone.

207
00:14:12,240 --> 00:14:16,160
According to my sixth sense,
that dependable student must be...

208
00:14:16,243 --> 00:14:17,953
...Mr. Morhange.

209
00:14:19,538 --> 00:14:22,791
Come on, come on.
Who is Mr. Morhange?

210
00:14:23,875 --> 00:14:25,585
That's me, sir.

211
00:14:32,425 --> 00:14:35,136
So you're the angel.

212
00:14:36,095 --> 00:14:39,848
Go down. You'll supervise
the class while I'm gone.

213
00:14:39,932 --> 00:14:41,600
Go on.

214
00:14:41,683 --> 00:14:45,937
Nice. You could pull out
your shirt a bit more.

215
00:14:46,020 --> 00:14:50,066
I'm told the rebellious have
strong leadership skills. Prove it.

216
00:14:51,025 --> 00:14:53,694
Come to the headmaster's office.

217
00:14:55,946 --> 00:14:58,323
- Have mercy, sir.
- Mercy?

218
00:14:58,407 --> 00:15:01,952
What about the boy who's taken
your place? And old Maxence?

219
00:15:01,993 --> 00:15:04,412
I didn't want to hurt him.
It was just a joke.

220
00:15:04,496 --> 00:15:06,081
A joke?

221
00:15:06,164 --> 00:15:11,002
...a little stint in lock-up.
I've had enough of you.

222
00:15:11,085 --> 00:15:14,422
But first, I'm going to give you
the flogging of your life.

223
00:15:17,383 --> 00:15:19,384
- Who is it?
- Leclerc.

224
00:15:19,426 --> 00:15:23,763
He's tried to run away three times.
He's taking him to lock-up.

225
00:15:23,805 --> 00:15:26,015
- So you won't be alone.
- Don't.

226
00:15:29,227 --> 00:15:32,730
Maybe we can come to an agreement.

227
00:15:32,813 --> 00:15:35,191
You hurt Mr. Maxence. Badly.

228
00:15:35,274 --> 00:15:38,610
I won't take you to the headmaster
but I have to punish you.

229
00:15:39,653 --> 00:15:44,282
Instead of fooling around during recess,
you'll work in the infirmary.

230
00:15:44,324 --> 00:15:46,743
You'll be old Maxence's nurse.

231
00:15:46,785 --> 00:15:49,412
You'll look after him until he's cured.

232
00:15:49,495 --> 00:15:50,872
All right?

233
00:16:08,930 --> 00:16:10,723
Not bad.

234
00:16:10,807 --> 00:16:12,516
What do you think?

235
00:16:12,600 --> 00:16:15,978
But I can do better. Give me the chalk.
Stand in profile.

236
00:16:16,061 --> 00:16:17,688
Profile.

237
00:16:30,908 --> 00:16:33,369
Let's see a smile for a change.

238
00:16:33,452 --> 00:16:36,247
You can look now.

239
00:16:36,288 --> 00:16:39,625
I almost forgot...
Some color would be nice.

240
00:16:43,044 --> 00:16:45,422
Much better. Get back to your seat.

241
00:16:47,090 --> 00:16:48,925
Very well.

242
00:16:49,008 --> 00:16:53,471
I want to get to know you,
so you're going to write your name,

243
00:16:53,554 --> 00:16:57,057
your age and your dream job
on a piece of paper.

244
00:17:03,063 --> 00:17:06,733
I was astonished when
they all did as they were told.

245
00:17:10,736 --> 00:17:13,531
All except one.

246
00:17:17,201 --> 00:17:19,119
You're not writing?

247
00:17:21,580 --> 00:17:24,457
How long have you been here?

248
00:17:24,499 --> 00:17:26,918
A long time?

249
00:17:26,960 --> 00:17:29,003
I don't know.

250
00:17:30,713 --> 00:17:32,715
Write, little fellow.

251
00:17:48,021 --> 00:17:50,565
An exhausting first day.

252
00:17:50,606 --> 00:17:53,734
I forgot why I came here
in the first place.

253
00:17:53,776 --> 00:17:57,863
Rachin scares me, the building
scares me, even the children scare me.

254
00:17:57,905 --> 00:18:02,117
I keep expecting them
to slip into my recess and murder me.

255
00:18:02,159 --> 00:18:03,618
My blanket.

256
00:18:04,786 --> 00:18:07,163
- Got a cigarette?
- Shut up.

257
00:18:07,247 --> 00:18:08,665
Go to bed.

258
00:18:23,595 --> 00:18:26,806
I read the assignments again.

259
00:18:26,890 --> 00:18:29,267
They all had fabulous dreams.

260
00:18:29,350 --> 00:18:32,603
Two firemen, three cowboys,
one tiger tamer, one fighter pilot,

261
00:18:32,687 --> 00:18:37,274
two spies, a general under Napoleon,
one balloonist, three legionaries...

262
00:18:38,233 --> 00:18:40,611
Not one school prefect.

263
00:18:42,237 --> 00:18:45,281
It was nice of you
to volunteer to be my nurse.

264
00:18:45,365 --> 00:18:50,536
Doctor, the new prefect asked
for a volunteer to take care of me.

265
00:18:50,578 --> 00:18:53,414
And he raised his hand right away.

266
00:18:53,456 --> 00:18:55,875
Proof that
we should believe in miracles.

267
00:18:55,916 --> 00:18:57,835
Come in.

268
00:18:57,918 --> 00:19:00,504
Mr. Mathieu, the new prefect.

269
00:19:02,339 --> 00:19:03,465
So?

270
00:19:03,548 --> 00:19:06,551
It's pretty bad, Maxence.

271
00:19:06,634 --> 00:19:09,512
If they've started attacking you,
they're beyond help.

272
00:19:09,595 --> 00:19:12,515
You're so patient with them.

273
00:19:12,598 --> 00:19:16,101
I've got a thick skull.
You shouldn't be feeling sorry for me.

274
00:19:16,185 --> 00:19:19,688
I feel sorry for those poor kids.
Don't forget one of them is dead.

275
00:19:19,771 --> 00:19:21,106
Dead?

276
00:19:21,189 --> 00:19:23,859
His name was Mouton.
He jumped off the roof.

277
00:19:23,942 --> 00:19:26,069
Good thing he was an orphan.

278
00:19:26,152 --> 00:19:29,197
Look at him. Everyone says
he's a lost cause. It's not true.

279
00:19:29,280 --> 00:19:32,617
He's a good boy.
You just have to know him.

280
00:19:32,700 --> 00:19:34,743
Old Maxence is a nice guy.

281
00:19:36,287 --> 00:19:39,831
I'm talking to you, Le Querrec.
Don't you think he's nice?

282
00:19:41,124 --> 00:19:43,043
No?

283
00:19:43,126 --> 00:19:44,085
Yes.

284
00:19:44,169 --> 00:19:46,546
- I didn't hear you.
- Leave him alone. He's shy.

285
00:19:46,629 --> 00:19:48,298
Like me.

286
00:19:49,841 --> 00:19:51,968
One, two, three, four...

287
00:19:54,303 --> 00:19:56,180
Faster.

288
00:19:58,599 --> 00:19:59,641
Yes?

289
00:19:59,725 --> 00:20:02,227
- I'd like a word, Headmaster.
- Leaving us so soon?

290
00:20:02,310 --> 00:20:05,647
- No, I'd like to try something.
- You don't say.

291
00:20:05,730 --> 00:20:08,733
About the accident.

292
00:20:08,816 --> 00:20:11,068
- That was no accident.
- Quite.

293
00:20:11,110 --> 00:20:13,070
I need three things from you.

294
00:20:13,154 --> 00:20:16,156
- Is that all?
- One, cancel the group punishment,

295
00:20:16,240 --> 00:20:21,995
two, let me deal with the culprit,
and three, don't ask me for his name.

296
00:20:22,120 --> 00:20:24,247
You'd have to know it first.

297
00:20:24,331 --> 00:20:25,707
Naturally.

298
00:20:25,790 --> 00:20:29,794
Your arrogance astounds me.
Do you really think you'll find him?

299
00:20:29,877 --> 00:20:33,631
Very well. If you succeed,
I'll cancel the group punishment.

300
00:20:33,714 --> 00:20:37,176
But you'll never get the culprit
or I'm the biggest fool in nature.

301
00:20:38,844 --> 00:20:41,471
I know who did it, Headmaster.

302
00:20:42,722 --> 00:20:44,849
Congratulations.

303
00:20:44,891 --> 00:20:47,310
Who is it?

304
00:20:47,393 --> 00:20:49,562
You said I wouldn't have to tell you.

305
00:20:50,938 --> 00:20:53,649
Fine. Very well then.

306
00:20:53,691 --> 00:20:55,693
But I don't like your manners.

307
00:20:55,776 --> 00:20:58,529
You'd better make sure
your students behave.

308
00:20:58,570 --> 00:21:02,074
- I've already got them under control.
- That's what you think.

309
00:21:02,115 --> 00:21:04,784
One, two, three, four... Go on.

310
00:21:05,952 --> 00:21:07,162
Faster.

311
00:21:20,632 --> 00:21:24,302
- There's no pictures of naked women.
- I never said there were naked women.

312
00:21:24,344 --> 00:21:26,262
What does yours say?

313
00:21:26,346 --> 00:21:30,016
"Ave Maria for soprano
by Clment Mathieu."

314
00:21:30,099 --> 00:21:33,519
I've got, "String quartet...

315
00:21:33,561 --> 00:21:36,605
...by Clment Mathieu."
- Looks like music.

316
00:21:36,689 --> 00:21:39,066
- What do you know about it?
- Maybe it's Morse.

317
00:21:39,149 --> 00:21:41,526
- Or some secret code.
- Maybe he's no prefect.

318
00:21:41,568 --> 00:21:43,904
Maybe he's an undercover spy.

319
00:21:43,987 --> 00:21:45,238
Chrome Dome.

320
00:21:55,581 --> 00:21:57,499
Give it back to me.

321
00:21:57,583 --> 00:22:00,085
- What is it, sir?
- None of your business.

322
00:22:00,168 --> 00:22:02,963
Is there a problem, Mathieu?

323
00:22:03,046 --> 00:22:05,131
No problem.

324
00:22:05,173 --> 00:22:07,091
It's just music.

325
00:22:07,175 --> 00:22:08,801
What for?

326
00:22:09,719 --> 00:22:11,137
A chorus.

327
00:22:12,138 --> 00:22:14,056
In the water closets?

328
00:22:15,558 --> 00:22:17,935
Clear out, chorus.

329
00:22:23,231 --> 00:22:25,734
- Not here, Mathieu.
- What?

330
00:22:25,817 --> 00:22:28,403
- Don't play the idiot.
- You're not suggesting...?

331
00:22:28,444 --> 00:22:30,446
I won't say anything this time.

332
00:22:31,489 --> 00:22:34,742
- You really see evil everywhere.
- In here? Yes.

333
00:22:41,873 --> 00:22:44,209
Baldy, you are through

334
00:22:44,251 --> 00:22:46,961
The rules won't be made by you

335
00:22:47,045 --> 00:22:49,422
Baldy, you are through

336
00:22:49,505 --> 00:22:51,799
The rules won't be made by you

337
00:23:07,438 --> 00:23:09,524
The rules won't be made by you

338
00:23:09,607 --> 00:23:11,859
Chickening out, guys?

339
00:23:13,652 --> 00:23:16,572
- You're Corbin.
- Yes, sir, but I didn't do anything.

340
00:23:16,655 --> 00:23:18,699
- You were singing.
- No, sir. I swear.

341
00:23:18,782 --> 00:23:22,661
You were singing. Badly.
And you couldn't even tell.

342
00:23:22,702 --> 00:23:24,162
Go on. Sing.

343
00:23:24,204 --> 00:23:26,664
I'm listening.

344
00:23:26,706 --> 00:23:30,001
Would you prefer to sing
for the headmaster? Go on.

345
00:23:30,084 --> 00:23:32,461
Chrome Dome
Prepare to meet your doom

346
00:23:33,504 --> 00:23:35,464
Chrome Dome
Prepare to meet your doom

347
00:23:35,506 --> 00:23:37,758
You're not the boss of us

348
00:23:37,841 --> 00:23:40,177
You're not the boss of us

349
00:23:40,218 --> 00:23:42,471
No one ever told you
you couldn't sing?

350
00:23:42,554 --> 00:23:45,682
Sir? Is that really music
in your satchel?

351
00:23:45,765 --> 00:23:47,767
Mind your own business.

352
00:23:49,394 --> 00:23:53,397
By the way, if I ever catch
one of you messing with my things...

353
00:23:54,899 --> 00:23:57,067
...he'll be very sorry.

354
00:23:57,109 --> 00:23:59,778
Now be quiet.
Time to go to bed. Hurry up.

355
00:23:59,820 --> 00:24:01,279
It's over.

356
00:24:15,751 --> 00:24:17,669
Go to sleep.

357
00:24:35,352 --> 00:24:38,313
I couldn't get their ditty
out of my head.

358
00:24:38,397 --> 00:24:41,608
They're not very good at it,
but they are singing.

359
00:24:41,692 --> 00:24:44,444
I even spotted a few good voices.

360
00:24:45,570 --> 00:24:48,990
Are those kids really a lost cause?

361
00:24:49,073 --> 00:24:51,993
And I had sworn never
to touch my music again.

362
00:24:53,661 --> 00:24:55,496
Never say never.

363
00:24:56,455 --> 00:24:59,208
Nothing is ever truly lost.

364
00:25:07,298 --> 00:25:09,008
January 23rd.

365
00:25:09,092 --> 00:25:13,012
One week after his accident, old Maxence
suddenly took a turn for the worse.

366
00:25:13,095 --> 00:25:15,681
The doctor sent him to the hospital.

367
00:25:20,644 --> 00:25:23,063
Is he going to die?

368
00:25:24,022 --> 00:25:26,274
No, we'll save him.

369
00:25:28,484 --> 00:25:30,903
The very same day,
Ppinot got into trouble.

370
00:25:30,945 --> 00:25:33,864
Mr. Ppinot, you're a dunce.

371
00:25:33,948 --> 00:25:38,619
Final question. The last one.
How did Marshal Ney die?

372
00:25:47,168 --> 00:25:48,836
I'm waiting.

373
00:25:59,138 --> 00:26:00,347
Hunting?

374
00:26:02,307 --> 00:26:03,225
Zero.

375
00:26:03,308 --> 00:26:06,686
One hundred lines by tomorrow:
"Marshal Ney was shot."

376
00:26:07,645 --> 00:26:09,105
Get out.

377
00:26:17,112 --> 00:26:19,323
Boniface. Come here, boy.

378
00:26:22,742 --> 00:26:25,328
Here, as a reward for your essay.

379
00:26:25,370 --> 00:26:27,622
Give it to Mrs. Marie
and you'll get a cookie.

380
00:26:27,705 --> 00:26:30,583
You knew Ney had been shot, eh?

381
00:26:30,666 --> 00:26:32,627
Of course, sir. Just like Napoleon.

382
00:26:34,503 --> 00:26:35,880
Get out.

383
00:26:36,839 --> 00:26:39,508
Hold on, Mr. Morhange.

384
00:26:39,591 --> 00:26:41,551
I saw you taking notes during class.

385
00:26:41,593 --> 00:26:46,222
This is a rare occurrence indeed.
Bring me your notebook.

386
00:27:02,070 --> 00:27:03,155
Charming.

387
00:27:07,450 --> 00:27:10,620
Read it.
Admire the spelling.

388
00:27:16,292 --> 00:27:19,586
"Mr. Rachin eats shit by the bushel."

389
00:27:19,670 --> 00:27:21,213
He wrote "Mr.?"

390
00:27:22,297 --> 00:27:23,548
No.

391
00:27:23,632 --> 00:27:26,468
Action-reaction, Mr. Mathieu.

392
00:27:26,551 --> 00:27:27,969
Lock-up.

393
00:27:33,432 --> 00:27:34,850
Come on.

394
00:27:55,828 --> 00:27:59,081
- Gentlemen, enjoy your meal.
- Thank you.

395
00:28:00,165 --> 00:28:02,167
Are you hungry, Ppinot?

396
00:28:07,547 --> 00:28:09,716
Now you can eat.

397
00:28:09,799 --> 00:28:11,175
Ppinot?

398
00:28:11,217 --> 00:28:12,551
He's an orphan.

399
00:28:12,593 --> 00:28:14,637
His parents died
during the Occupation.

400
00:28:15,638 --> 00:28:17,639
- How did they die?
- I don't know.

401
00:28:17,681 --> 00:28:20,684
The kid thinks his father
will come for him on a Saturday.

402
00:28:22,519 --> 00:28:24,521
No one ever comes on Saturday.

403
00:28:24,604 --> 00:28:27,524
So we tell him he'll come
next Saturday, and so on.

404
00:28:27,607 --> 00:28:29,609
It'd be easier to tell him the truth.

405
00:28:29,650 --> 00:28:32,737
We must have told him 100 times.
He won't listen.

406
00:28:32,820 --> 00:28:37,449
Now we let him wait by the gate.
Let him enjoy himself.

407
00:28:38,909 --> 00:28:40,577
Be quiet!

408
00:28:42,162 --> 00:28:45,081
Did you see that? Action-reaction.

409
00:28:45,165 --> 00:28:46,624
Meaning?

410
00:28:46,708 --> 00:28:48,167
Action.

411
00:28:48,209 --> 00:28:49,752
Reaction.

412
00:28:49,836 --> 00:28:52,380
There's a visitor for young Morhange.

413
00:28:52,463 --> 00:28:54,298
Morhange is in lock-up.

414
00:28:54,381 --> 00:28:56,759
No visitors for the punished.
You know the rules.

415
00:28:56,842 --> 00:28:59,678
Go tell his visitor then.

416
00:29:24,075 --> 00:29:25,827
Good day, madame.

417
00:29:25,910 --> 00:29:27,328
Good day.

418
00:29:27,370 --> 00:29:29,414
I'm the new prefect.

419
00:29:30,123 --> 00:29:31,999
I'm Pierre Morhange's mother.

420
00:29:32,083 --> 00:29:33,959
Clment Mathieu.

421
00:29:34,001 --> 00:29:37,921
I know this isn't the right day,
but it's the only time I could...

422
00:29:38,005 --> 00:29:41,299
- No, that's not the problem.
- Has he been punished again?

423
00:29:41,383 --> 00:29:43,802
No, nothing like that...

424
00:29:43,885 --> 00:29:46,179
...but he's not here.

425
00:29:46,221 --> 00:29:48,264
What do you mean?

426
00:29:48,348 --> 00:29:51,601
They took him to the dentist.
He had a toothache.

427
00:29:51,684 --> 00:29:53,227
A toothache?

428
00:29:53,310 --> 00:29:56,897
Yes, but nothing serious.
He'll be back tonight.

429
00:29:57,981 --> 00:30:01,151
I can't wait.
I'm going back to work at 5.

430
00:30:02,152 --> 00:30:04,070
Can I leave something for him?

431
00:30:04,154 --> 00:30:06,114
Of course.

432
00:30:09,283 --> 00:30:12,995
Her name is Violette.
Violette Morhange.

433
00:30:13,037 --> 00:30:15,915
A single mother at her wits' end
about her son,

434
00:30:15,998 --> 00:30:20,961
a thieving introvert expelled from
school because he kept running away.

435
00:30:21,003 --> 00:30:25,006
When Pierre was sent to Fond de
I'tang against his mother's wishes,

436
00:30:25,090 --> 00:30:29,802
she told the judge, "At least
he'll get a hot meal twice a day."

437
00:30:31,971 --> 00:30:34,223
January 30th. The experience begins.

438
00:30:34,515 --> 00:30:37,476
In Brittany, the hats are...

439
00:30:37,976 --> 00:30:41,188
In Brittany, the hats are round

440
00:30:41,271 --> 00:30:44,441
That's why I'm Brittany bound

441
00:30:44,482 --> 00:30:47,485
Soprano. Go left.

442
00:30:47,527 --> 00:30:49,153
Leclerc.

443
00:30:51,447 --> 00:30:56,035
He is born, the Holy Child
Let us greet His coming

444
00:30:56,118 --> 00:30:58,495
Almost in tune.
Alto, go left.

445
00:30:59,329 --> 00:31:00,789
Delaire.

446
00:31:03,041 --> 00:31:06,419
Three miles on foot
What does it use?

447
00:31:06,503 --> 00:31:09,130
Three miles on foot
eats up your shoes

448
00:31:09,213 --> 00:31:10,631
Do it again.

449
00:31:10,715 --> 00:31:13,718
Four miles on foot
What does it use?

450
00:31:13,801 --> 00:31:16,178
Four miles on foot
eats up your shoes

451
00:31:16,262 --> 00:31:19,515
I was right. Bass, go right.

452
00:31:19,556 --> 00:31:21,016
Ricoeur.

453
00:31:23,393 --> 00:31:27,188
I've got tobacco in my pouch

454
00:31:27,230 --> 00:31:29,148
I'll give it away, not today

455
00:31:29,232 --> 00:31:32,109
Smoking is strictly forbidden.
Alto, left.

456
00:31:33,069 --> 00:31:34,612
Illouz.

457
00:31:37,698 --> 00:31:40,492
Love is a gypsy child

458
00:31:40,575 --> 00:31:43,411
That obeys no one's laws

459
00:31:43,453 --> 00:31:46,664
Soprano, of course. Left.

460
00:31:46,748 --> 00:31:48,875
Very well. Ppinot.

461
00:31:52,545 --> 00:31:54,422
I don't know any songs.

462
00:31:54,505 --> 00:31:56,757
That's fine. I'll teach you some.

463
00:31:58,175 --> 00:32:02,220
In the meantime,
you can be Assistant Chorus Master.

464
00:32:04,472 --> 00:32:05,724
Over there.

465
00:32:08,601 --> 00:32:11,187
Boniface.

466
00:32:12,938 --> 00:32:15,941
Marshal Ptain, here we are

467
00:32:16,025 --> 00:32:19,278
- Who taught you that?
- My grandfather.

468
00:32:19,319 --> 00:32:21,655
A little old-fashioned. Left.

469
00:32:22,531 --> 00:32:23,657
Clment.

470
00:32:25,992 --> 00:32:29,495
Citizens to arms
Display your charms

471
00:32:29,579 --> 00:32:30,955
Enough. Right.

472
00:32:30,997 --> 00:32:33,040
My camp counselor's a jerk

473
00:32:33,082 --> 00:32:35,793
He doesn't do any work

474
00:32:35,834 --> 00:32:36,877
Go left.

475
00:32:36,919 --> 00:32:39,922
Cuckoo, booboo
Cuckoo, booboo

476
00:32:43,175 --> 00:32:44,509
Good. Alto.

477
00:32:55,060 --> 00:32:57,062
Strong beat.

478
00:32:57,146 --> 00:32:58,856
Strong beat.

479
00:33:11,826 --> 00:33:13,661
Show me, Corbin.

480
00:33:20,876 --> 00:33:23,837
Sorry, there's no such note.
Come here.

481
00:33:24,879 --> 00:33:27,215
Mr. Ppinot, hand me the score.

482
00:33:27,674 --> 00:33:30,384
Thank you. Open your hands.

483
00:33:30,468 --> 00:33:32,970
Hold them like this.

484
00:33:33,054 --> 00:33:34,930
Good. You can be our lectern.

485
00:33:36,849 --> 00:33:38,475
Baton, Mr. Ppinot.

486
00:33:39,476 --> 00:33:41,061
Thank you.

487
00:33:43,021 --> 00:33:44,898
Get ready. On three...

488
00:33:52,238 --> 00:33:53,155
Again.

489
00:33:57,242 --> 00:33:58,702
That's it.

490
00:33:58,785 --> 00:34:00,454
One, two, three, four.

491
00:34:00,537 --> 00:34:03,540
Le Querrec's on bread and water...

492
00:34:03,623 --> 00:34:06,709
Every night, I make them practice
a simple tune of my own.

493
00:34:06,793 --> 00:34:09,796
Carpentier has lost his way

494
00:34:09,837 --> 00:34:13,507
Fond de I'Etang is where
we're stuck, just our luck

495
00:34:13,549 --> 00:34:17,177
Fond de I'Etang is where we'll be
for all eternity

496
00:34:25,643 --> 00:34:27,437
Not bad.

497
00:34:27,478 --> 00:34:30,356
It wasn't Mozart,
but I had their attention now.

498
00:34:30,440 --> 00:34:34,026
From now on, I would need
the support of my superiors.

499
00:34:34,068 --> 00:34:36,487
What?

500
00:34:36,570 --> 00:34:38,405
A chorus?

501
00:34:38,489 --> 00:34:39,656
Yes.

502
00:34:39,740 --> 00:34:43,535
My poor man, you've completely lost it.

503
00:34:43,577 --> 00:34:47,205
A chorus. You won't get a single note
from them or I'm the biggest fool...

504
00:34:47,247 --> 00:34:49,791
Please, Headmaster,
don't finish your sentence.

505
00:34:49,832 --> 00:34:51,500
Why not?

506
00:34:51,584 --> 00:34:53,419
They're singing already.

507
00:34:53,502 --> 00:34:54,920
Really?

508
00:34:54,962 --> 00:34:56,380
Just a few notes.

509
00:34:56,422 --> 00:34:59,883
Why ask my permission
if you're already doing it?

510
00:34:59,967 --> 00:35:01,885
I don't like your manners.

511
00:35:01,968 --> 00:35:04,471
- Headmaster...
- You're annoying me.

512
00:35:04,554 --> 00:35:06,598
I have other things on my mind.

513
00:35:06,681 --> 00:35:09,892
Very well. I enjoy a good laugh.

514
00:35:09,934 --> 00:35:11,811
Make them sing.

515
00:35:11,852 --> 00:35:15,064
But if everything goes sour,
you'll lose your job.

516
00:35:18,358 --> 00:35:20,861
Thank you for your support, Headmaster.

517
00:35:25,573 --> 00:35:27,158
February 8th.

518
00:35:27,242 --> 00:35:30,578
As we begin rehearsals,
Rachin starts on Morhange.

519
00:35:30,661 --> 00:35:33,289
As soon as he's out of lock-up,
he lowers the axe:

520
00:35:33,372 --> 00:35:35,332
